00:03:09.150 --> 00:03:12.910
So, I have a very
straightforward way

00:03:12.910 --> 00:03:14.360
of making jam.

00:03:14.360 --> 00:03:19.360
And one my things about making
jam is that all you're doing,

00:03:19.360 --> 00:03:21.540
and what you need
to focus on most,

00:03:21.540 --> 00:03:27.770
is your main purpose with jam
is to remove water and implement

00:03:27.770 --> 00:03:28.620
sugar.

00:03:28.620 --> 00:03:30.160
That's all you're doing.

00:03:30.160 --> 00:03:32.720
So this heating
process, all we're doing

00:03:32.720 --> 00:03:35.000
is helping the water evaporate.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:37.860
And we're breaking down
fruit and impregnating

00:03:37.860 --> 00:03:40.010
what is left over with sugar.

00:03:40.010 --> 00:03:41.540
That's it.

00:03:41.540 --> 00:03:44.490
I am not an advocate of pectin.

00:03:44.490 --> 00:03:49.340
I think that pectin creates an
unnatural, overly gelatinous

00:03:49.340 --> 00:03:52.970
texture, and detracts
from the fruit.

00:03:52.970 --> 00:03:56.850
We are incredibly lucky
here in Southern California

00:03:56.850 --> 00:04:01.330
to be able to get just the
most gorgeous produce any day

00:04:01.330 --> 00:04:02.040
of the week.

00:04:02.040 --> 00:04:04.930
You know, I talk to people
in the Pacific Northwest,

00:04:04.930 --> 00:04:07.940
on the east coast, and they're
like, you got what today?

00:04:07.940 --> 00:04:09.370
You got blueberries today?

00:04:09.370 --> 00:04:10.520
That's bizarre.

00:04:10.520 --> 00:04:11.620
We have squash here.

00:04:11.620 --> 00:04:13.120
That's all we have.

00:04:13.120 --> 00:04:17.240
So here in sunny
Los Angeles, it's

00:04:17.240 --> 00:04:20.304
like year round you can
make delicious jams.

00:04:23.230 --> 00:04:26.790
I also think one of the reasons
why jamming, marmalades,

00:04:26.790 --> 00:04:30.090
pickles, all this stuff
has become so popular

00:04:30.090 --> 00:04:32.720
is because of where
produce is at today.

00:04:32.720 --> 00:04:35.230
Because we see these
farmers markets

00:04:35.230 --> 00:04:38.640
in every neighborhood
every day of the week.

00:04:38.640 --> 00:04:42.580
And we get to take
advantage of it.

00:04:42.580 --> 00:04:43.370
So, jam.

00:04:43.370 --> 00:04:47.030
Today I'm making what I think
is pretty much the easiest

00:04:47.030 --> 00:04:48.790
kind of jam that you can make.

00:04:48.790 --> 00:04:50.250
Anyone can do this.

00:04:50.250 --> 00:04:54.170
So all I did was I cut up
five pounds of strawberries,

00:04:54.170 --> 00:04:56.000
fresh strawberries.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:59.470
And my magic ratio
is five pounds

00:04:59.470 --> 00:05:02.180
of fruit to four cups of sugar.

00:05:02.180 --> 00:05:04.030
That is a great starting point.

00:05:04.030 --> 00:05:06.490
And some of you who've
made jam before may say,

00:05:06.490 --> 00:05:07.990
that's a really low
amount of sugar.

00:05:07.990 --> 00:05:09.380
That's absolutely correct.

00:05:09.380 --> 00:05:13.230
Because jam should taste
like fruit and not sugar.

00:05:13.230 --> 00:05:17.900
And I use just enough for
you to safely preserve it.

00:05:17.900 --> 00:05:20.430
You know, sugar's like salt.

00:05:20.430 --> 00:05:22.690
Once you add it, you
can't take it out.

00:05:22.690 --> 00:05:26.220
So it's good to start low
and then slowly increase

00:05:26.220 --> 00:05:30.050
as you're cooking and tasting.

00:05:30.050 --> 00:05:32.220
The way I generally
cook jams, the way

00:05:32.220 --> 00:05:35.350
I advise to cook jams in
the book, is to macerate.

00:05:35.350 --> 00:05:41.490
Macerate means to let the
fruit sit for a bit of time

00:05:41.490 --> 00:05:42.670
with sugar.

00:05:42.670 --> 00:05:46.350
What that does is that actually
reduces your cooking time,

00:05:46.350 --> 00:05:49.350
which is a really nice thing.

00:05:49.350 --> 00:05:50.930
The first few
times I made jam, I

00:05:50.930 --> 00:05:54.419
had some very experienced
pastry chefs show me how.

00:05:54.419 --> 00:05:55.710
And I was just sort of curious.

00:05:55.710 --> 00:05:57.470
Like, what's your jam process?

00:05:57.470 --> 00:05:58.180
What's your deal?

00:05:58.180 --> 00:06:01.020
You know what I mean?

00:06:01.020 --> 00:06:03.530
And I was shown some
rather torturous methods

00:06:03.530 --> 00:06:07.150
for jam making, where you
stand over the pot for hours

00:06:07.150 --> 00:06:08.020
and hours and hours.

00:06:08.020 --> 00:06:11.510
And this thing's like
splashing in your face.

00:06:11.510 --> 00:06:13.040
And I was like,
well, I don't really

00:06:13.040 --> 00:06:16.600
have time to stir a pot
for two hours, personally.

00:06:16.600 --> 00:06:18.265
And most people don't.

00:06:18.265 --> 00:06:19.350
You know what I mean?

00:06:19.350 --> 00:06:22.200
It's like that's where
people sort of step away

00:06:22.200 --> 00:06:24.580
from making things
to buying things.

00:06:24.580 --> 00:06:28.980
If you macerate fruit, that
will cut down your cooking time.

00:06:28.980 --> 00:06:31.240
It actually cuts down
your active time.

00:06:31.240 --> 00:06:36.620
And it tends to extract more
of the juices from the fruit.

00:06:36.620 --> 00:06:40.670
So while that sugar is
sitting with the fruit,

00:06:40.670 --> 00:06:43.870
with the prepared fruit, it
starts to break down the fruit.

00:06:43.870 --> 00:06:45.930
The sugars start to
come out of the fruit.

00:06:45.930 --> 00:06:50.270
So you get a really
great, full flavor.

00:06:50.270 --> 00:06:52.250
From there-- and what
I generally advise

00:06:52.250 --> 00:06:53.580
is to macerate for an hour.

00:06:53.580 --> 00:06:56.420
You could also stick it in your
refrigerator for a day or two.

00:06:56.420 --> 00:06:58.780
So this can break up the
activity a little bit.

00:06:58.780 --> 00:07:00.850
Say you're making
strawberry vanilla bean jam.

00:07:00.850 --> 00:07:02.070
Say you're making plum jam.

00:07:02.070 --> 00:07:03.070
You're making peach jam.

00:07:03.070 --> 00:07:06.720
Whatever it is, say you've
got a half hour in your day.

00:07:06.720 --> 00:07:09.460
You can prepare the
fruit, mix it with sugar,

00:07:09.460 --> 00:07:12.810
cover it, put it in your
refrigerator for half a day,

00:07:12.810 --> 00:07:13.910
for a day.

00:07:13.910 --> 00:07:15.130
The next day, you come back.

00:07:15.130 --> 00:07:17.380
And then you cook it and
can it, or just cook it

00:07:17.380 --> 00:07:19.290
and store it in
the refrigerator.

00:07:19.290 --> 00:07:23.280
I think it makes it just sort of
a more reasonable and realistic

00:07:23.280 --> 00:07:25.150
process for those
of us that work

00:07:25.150 --> 00:07:27.720
and have children
and have lives.

00:07:27.720 --> 00:07:32.720
Most people can't just
spend two days making jam

00:07:32.720 --> 00:07:34.960
at their leisure.

00:07:34.960 --> 00:07:39.320
But that would be cool, but
most people can't do that.

00:07:39.320 --> 00:07:41.860
So right now, all I'm doing,
I have this on a high heat.

00:07:41.860 --> 00:07:43.330
And it's always good to
start at a high heat.

00:07:43.330 --> 00:07:44.600
We just want to break it down.

00:07:44.600 --> 00:07:47.450
We just want to break down the
fruit and get rid of the water.

00:07:47.450 --> 00:07:51.320
So we have to bring this
concoction up to boiling.

00:07:51.320 --> 00:07:52.960
That's the first
thing that we do.

00:07:52.960 --> 00:07:55.360
And you move it a little
bit, but again, you

00:07:55.360 --> 00:07:58.810
don't have to stand
here and work yourself

00:07:58.810 --> 00:08:00.250
into a massive sweat.

00:08:00.250 --> 00:08:04.320
Like there's a significant
amount of water in here,

00:08:04.320 --> 00:08:07.620
and it'll just start to
boil, almost like soup.

00:08:07.620 --> 00:08:12.200
And we just keep an eye on
it, stirring it occasionally.

00:08:12.200 --> 00:08:19.090
Right now, what I might do
is already take a taste.

00:08:19.090 --> 00:08:20.690
You always want to
taste as you cook.

00:08:20.690 --> 00:08:21.710
Put it in your mouth.

00:08:21.710 --> 00:08:24.340
Or else you have no
idea what you're doing.

00:08:24.340 --> 00:08:26.060
Don't wait until the end.

00:08:26.060 --> 00:08:28.690
Because if you're
making jam, whatever

00:08:28.690 --> 00:08:31.440
it is that you're making,
don't wait until the end.

00:08:31.440 --> 00:08:33.630
Taste as you go,
taste as you go.

00:08:33.630 --> 00:08:38.429
And tweak in a way that's
most appealing to your palate.

00:08:38.429 --> 00:08:42.704
So that totally is enough sugar.

00:08:42.704 --> 00:08:44.370
So I'm not going to
do anything to that.

00:08:44.370 --> 00:08:47.900
I'm just going to totally leave
that alone and add our vanilla

00:08:47.900 --> 00:08:48.400
beans.

00:08:48.400 --> 00:08:50.360
So vanilla beans,
these are great.

00:08:50.360 --> 00:08:51.740
These are gorgeous pods.

00:08:51.740 --> 00:08:55.230
And if you get them,
you want to break down

00:08:55.230 --> 00:08:56.510
the vanilla bean a little bit.

00:08:56.510 --> 00:08:59.160
And by rolling it between
your fingers like this--

00:08:59.160 --> 00:09:02.250
you do generally store vanilla
beans in the refrigerator.

00:09:02.250 --> 00:09:04.000
Let them come to
room temperature

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:05.650
before you start
to play with them.

00:09:05.650 --> 00:09:07.858
And then you want to roll
them a little bit like this

00:09:07.858 --> 00:09:11.780
to loosen the beans
inside from the pod.

00:09:11.780 --> 00:09:14.040
You can scrape the
beans off a lot easier

00:09:14.040 --> 00:09:15.410
that way if you do that.

00:09:15.410 --> 00:09:18.660
So the whole thing,
top to bottom,

00:09:18.660 --> 00:09:22.230
I'm just rolling it
in my fingertips.

00:09:22.230 --> 00:09:25.970
And then you take the
sharp paring knife.

00:09:25.970 --> 00:09:28.300
And you just run it down
the center of the bean.

00:09:35.130 --> 00:09:37.335
And then you fan it
open, just like this.

00:09:40.270 --> 00:09:42.460
And then you want to
scrape out those beans.

00:09:42.460 --> 00:09:47.620
It's really, really pretty,
and incredibly aromatic.

00:09:47.620 --> 00:09:50.440
So we just scrape that out.

00:09:50.440 --> 00:09:52.800
And this whole thing
is going into the pot.

00:09:52.800 --> 00:09:59.340
The pod and the beans impart a
really wonderful, warm, sweet,

00:09:59.340 --> 00:10:03.640
delicious vanilla bean
flavor to this jam.

00:10:03.640 --> 00:10:05.220
And then we stir that in.

00:10:05.220 --> 00:10:07.304
If you're a big
fan of vanilla bean

00:10:07.304 --> 00:10:08.720
and you're making
this jam, or you

00:10:08.720 --> 00:10:12.320
decide to add vanilla bean to
whatever, and you're macerating

00:10:12.320 --> 00:10:14.850
and you really want to see
a lot of that vanilla bean,

00:10:14.850 --> 00:10:17.350
you want to taste a lot of
that vanilla mean, put it

00:10:17.350 --> 00:10:19.550
in a before you macerate.

00:10:19.550 --> 00:10:24.090
And that will increase the
amount of vanilla bean flavor.

00:10:24.090 --> 00:10:27.160
You can also put a vanilla
bean in a bottle of vodka.

00:10:27.160 --> 00:10:29.060
And it does a really
good thing if you

00:10:29.060 --> 00:10:31.005
go in that direction, FYI.

00:10:34.640 --> 00:10:35.860
Any questions?

00:10:35.860 --> 00:10:37.800
